SIMPLE: breadth
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Breadth
<hw>Breadth</hw> <pr>(br⟦ecr⟧dth)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>brede</ets>, <ets>breede</ets>, whence later <ets>bredette</ets>,
AS. <ets>br⟦aemac⟧du</ets>, fr. <ets>br⟦amac⟧d</ets> broad. See
<er>Broad</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Distance from side to side of any surface or thing;
measure across, or at right angles to the length; width.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> The quality of having the colors
and shadows broad and massive, and the arrangement of objects such as to
avoid to great multiplicity of details, producing an impression of
largeness and simple grandeur; -- called also <altname>breadth of
effect</altname>.</p>

<p><q><qex>Breadth</qex> of coloring is a prominent character in the
painting of all great masters.</q> <rj><qau>Weale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Breadthless</ent>⟦br⟧
